A x B = {(2, 4), (2, 5), (3, 4), (3, 5)}
B x C = {(4, 6), (4, 7), (5, 6), (5, 7)}

Now, we can compute (A x B) x C and A x (B x C).

(A x B) x C = {((2, 4), 6), ((2, 4), 7), ((2, 5), 6), ((2, 5), 7), ((3, 4), 6), ((3, 4), 7), ((3, 5), 6), ((3, 5), 7)}

A x (B x C) = {(2, (4, 6)), (2, (4, 7)), (2, (5, 6)), (2, (5, 7)), (3, (4, 6)), (3, (4, 7)), (3, (5, 6)), (3, (5, 7))}

Now, let's rewrite the elements of (A x B) x C and A x (B x C) in a more comparable form:

(A x B) x C = {(2, 4, 6), (2, 4, 7), (2, 5, 6), (2, 5, 7), (3, 4, 6), (3, 4, 7), (3, 5, 6), (3, 5, 7)}

A x (B x C) = {(2, 4, 6), (2, 4, 7), (2, 5, 6), (2, 5, 7), (3, 4, 6), (3, 4, 7), (3, 5, 6), (3, 5, 7)}

As we can see, the sets (A x B) x C and A x (B x C) are equal. Therefore, the Cartesian product of two sets is associative.
